01:59.520 --> 02:02.022
Many visitors
come to Trinidad for one thing

02:02.055 --> 02:04.625
and one thing only, Carnival,

02:04.658 --> 02:07.461
which locals say is
the biggest party on Earth,

02:07.495 --> 02:09.763
a pre-Lenten festival
of costumes,

02:09.797 --> 02:12.766
food, copious drinking,
and the kind of dancing

02:12.800 --> 02:16.204
you'd better be good at
before trying in public.

02:16.237 --> 02:19.607
It's almost two months before
the party officially starts,

02:19.640 --> 02:21.975
but here in Trinidad's capital,
Port of Spain,

02:22.009 --> 02:25.813
the Carnival season
has already begun.

02:25.846 --> 02:28.649
I thought it was a pity
that you weren't here

02:28.682 --> 02:30.551
during the peak
of the Carnival season.

02:30.584 --> 02:33.554
I'll tell you something
really terrible about myself.

02:33.587 --> 02:36.690
Like, I've never been to
Mardi Gras, Carnival in Rio,

02:36.724 --> 02:38.226
any kind of Carnival.
Okay.

02:38.259 --> 02:39.960
Like, large numbers
of strangers...

02:39.993 --> 02:41.562
That is very interesting.

02:41.595 --> 02:43.797
Swarming through the streets
dancing in uniforms?

02:43.831 --> 02:46.367
- Doesn't do it for you?
- No. Some of my deepest fears

02:46.400 --> 02:49.803
are having to dance
or sing in public.

02:49.837 --> 02:51.672
Either of these
would be terrifying,

02:51.705 --> 02:53.574
so this seems like a situation

02:53.607 --> 02:56.076
where that might come up,
you know?

02:59.112 --> 03:01.882
♪

03:01.915 --> 03:05.986
Queen's Park Savannah will be
the epicenter of Carnival,

03:06.019 --> 03:09.923
but tonight it's still
Trinidad's street food center.

03:09.957 --> 03:13.761
♪

03:13.794 --> 03:16.029
My dinner companion
for some fried snapper

03:16.063 --> 03:17.731
is La Shaun Prescott,

03:17.765 --> 03:20.334
who's here to tell me
about two essential skills

03:20.368 --> 03:23.604
necessary for the proper
enjoyment of local nightlife.

03:23.637 --> 03:29.777
Turns out I am very good at one
and suck epically at the other.

03:29.810 --> 03:31.078
What is liming?

03:31.111 --> 03:34.548
Liming is, like, our version
of hanging out, you know?

03:34.582 --> 03:37.217
- Right.
- You're with friends.

03:37.251 --> 03:38.886
You're chilling.
That's liming.

03:38.919 --> 03:41.114
Is there alcohol involved?
Chances are if you're liming...

03:41.121 --> 03:42.456
Of course, probably.

03:42.490 --> 03:44.124
Well, I mean,
you can lime without beer.

03:44.157 --> 03:46.960
What about the rum?
I haven't had any rum here.

03:46.994 --> 03:48.462
How does one drink rum here,

03:48.496 --> 03:49.804
and which rum should
I be drinking?

03:49.830 --> 03:51.432
Does one drink it
on the rocks or mixed?

03:51.465 --> 03:53.301
- So one drinks it with Coke.
- With Coke?

03:53.334 --> 03:54.968
Yeah, rum and Coke.

03:55.002 --> 03:56.630
But the rum's supposed to be
really, really good here.

03:56.637 --> 03:57.638
Yeah.

03:59.807 --> 04:01.809
Okay, so we've established
what liming is.

04:01.842 --> 04:03.877
What is wining?

04:06.847 --> 04:10.318
The technical term is
the circumduction of the hips,

04:10.351 --> 04:12.720
and it's a style of dance.

04:12.753 --> 04:13.987
♪

04:14.021 --> 04:16.624
And if you're not used
to the culture,

04:16.656 --> 04:17.918
you don't understand
what it means,

04:17.925 --> 04:19.593
you can interpret it
the wrong way.

04:19.627 --> 04:21.295
When you see it
for the first time,

04:21.329 --> 04:23.997
you can think it's seductive,
you can think it's sexual.

04:24.031 --> 04:26.334
♪

04:26.367 --> 04:28.436
But people can wine
on each other

04:28.469 --> 04:29.970
and not really mean anything.
Right.

04:30.003 --> 04:31.532
I could wine on you,
and it doesn't mean

04:31.539 --> 04:33.140
that I want
to take you home, you know?

04:33.173 --> 04:35.343
It's something
that's really about freedom

04:35.376 --> 04:37.144
of expression of self,

04:37.177 --> 04:41.982
and it's something
that crosses ages, races,

04:42.015 --> 04:45.753
ethnicities, especially
during Carnival time.

04:45.786 --> 04:48.989
You see people from high status
and people who are,

04:49.022 --> 04:51.525
you know, lower class,
they both wine together.

04:51.559 --> 04:53.927
You know, the barriers
are no longer there.

04:53.961 --> 04:57.998
It's all just a mix of all
different ethnicities and stuff.

04:58.031 --> 05:00.267
♪

05:03.236 --> 05:05.038
♪

05:05.072 --> 05:08.041
The faces you see
in the streets are African,

05:08.075 --> 05:09.377
Indian, Chinese,

05:09.410 --> 05:11.311
Middle Eastern in features

05:11.345 --> 05:14.982
and every shade of mix
in between.

05:15.015 --> 05:17.685
This patchwork of ethnic
identities and colors

05:17.718 --> 05:21.889
is a direct legacy
of Trinidad's colonial past.

05:21.922 --> 05:24.625
Located at the southern end
of the Caribbean Sea,

05:24.658 --> 05:27.327
seven miles offshore
from Venezuela,

05:27.361 --> 05:29.363
Trinidad and Tobago
have long been

05:29.397 --> 05:31.399
important ports of call.

05:35.936 --> 05:38.238
Like a lot of islands
in the area,

05:38.271 --> 05:41.675
everybody's been through here
at one point or another.

05:41.709 --> 05:44.412
The usual European
hunters of fortune.

05:44.445 --> 05:46.246
The Spanish came
looking for gold.

05:46.279 --> 05:50.083
Then the Dutch, French,
and British took their turns

05:50.117 --> 05:52.753
at the real money
of the time, sugar,

05:52.786 --> 05:57.190
an economy built on
plantation labor and slavery.

05:57.224 --> 06:01.328
Finally, the island hit
the big money...

06:01.361 --> 06:03.731
oil.

06:14.307 --> 06:16.043
During World War II,

06:16.076 --> 06:18.011
a pair of seemingly
unrelated events

06:18.045 --> 06:21.482
had a big impact on
the island's musical culture.

06:26.654 --> 06:28.722
The U.S. Navy
built an oil depot

06:28.756 --> 06:31.459
to supply overseas
strategic needs.

06:35.128 --> 06:37.631
And the ruling
British banned drums

06:37.665 --> 06:39.800
made from traditional-style
animal skins

06:39.833 --> 06:41.702
after a series of riots

06:41.735 --> 06:45.205
they insisted were inspired
by African drumming.

06:45.238 --> 06:48.308
♪

06:48.341 --> 06:51.479
One improvises
in such circumstances,

06:51.512 --> 06:54.314
and all those oil drums
were repurposed.

06:54.347 --> 06:57.751
♪

07:01.021 --> 07:01.521
♪

07:06.359 --> 07:10.263
This is Phase II, one of only
11 large steel bands

07:10.297 --> 07:13.300
taking part in the worldwide
competition, Panorama,

07:13.333 --> 07:15.335
that happens in a few weeks.

07:15.368 --> 07:18.005
Winner gets 150 grand.

07:18.038 --> 07:20.808
♪

07:20.841 --> 07:23.010
They've taken home
the prize seven times,

07:23.043 --> 07:25.445
in no small part
due to this man,

07:25.479 --> 07:27.114
Lennox "Boogsie" Sharpe.

07:27.147 --> 07:27.647
♪

07:35.723 --> 07:37.825
The rehearsal space
is called a pan yard,

07:37.858 --> 07:41.128
and if you're lucky, somebody
nearby is making this,

07:41.161 --> 07:43.531
corn soup,

07:43.564 --> 07:44.932
split pea broth,

07:44.965 --> 07:48.636
dumplings, and, of course, corn.

07:48.669 --> 07:50.971
Kim Johnson is a local
journalist and historian

07:51.004 --> 07:52.640
who knows about this stuff.

07:52.673 --> 07:56.009
It's far more complex
than you think.

07:56.043 --> 07:56.543
♪

08:00.981 --> 08:03.784
Wow. I got to tell you,
that was incredible.

08:03.817 --> 08:06.053
I heard a lot of, you know,
little steel drum bands

08:06.086 --> 08:09.857
around the Caribbean,
but nothing like that.

08:09.890 --> 08:12.526
All percussion, right? 100%?
Yes.

08:12.560 --> 08:15.195
How did your interest
in this develop?

08:15.228 --> 08:18.131
I grew up here.
Later I became a writer.

08:18.165 --> 08:22.135
I discovered there
just hundreds of stories.

08:24.605 --> 08:26.974
Because in the early days,

08:27.007 --> 08:29.376
up until the
'60s the steel bands

08:29.409 --> 08:31.845
were partly like...
Like street gangs.

08:31.879 --> 08:33.847
They would fight one another,

08:33.881 --> 08:35.749
the "West Side Story"
kind of thing.

08:35.783 --> 08:38.485
The steel bands doubled as that.

08:38.518 --> 08:39.018
♪

08:42.623 --> 08:44.858
So I just got fascinated

08:44.892 --> 08:47.060
by tracking down
all of these pioneers

08:47.094 --> 08:49.396
and getting their stories
of how they got involved.

08:49.429 --> 08:51.498
I'll been 64 years this year.

08:51.531 --> 08:52.833
I play music since I was a kid.

08:52.866 --> 08:54.735
And his story is that
he grew up with them

08:54.768 --> 08:56.103
in one of his back yards.

08:56.136 --> 08:57.771
When he was about
three years old,

08:57.805 --> 08:59.773
he was going out
playing with them.

09:03.043 --> 09:05.779
♪

09:05.813 --> 09:07.280
Boogsie composes his pieces

09:07.314 --> 09:09.349
by layering different
types of drums

09:09.382 --> 09:10.951
on top of each other.

09:10.984 --> 09:13.553
Engine Room,
made of unpitched percussion,

09:13.587 --> 09:15.088
lays down the groove.

09:15.122 --> 09:15.622
♪

09:20.427 --> 09:24.131
Next, a section of six
bass pans drops a bass line.

09:24.164 --> 09:24.664
♪

09:31.739 --> 09:34.307
The guitar and cello pans
add harmonies

09:34.341 --> 09:37.711
that sound like strumming.

09:37.745 --> 09:38.245
♪

09:46.119 --> 09:49.289
And the frontline pans
play the melody.

09:49.322 --> 09:49.822
♪

09:57.765 --> 10:00.600
The result?
A symphonic wall of sound.

10:00.634 --> 10:01.969
♪

10:02.002 --> 10:05.005
I'd like someday
to marriage this

10:05.038 --> 10:07.107
with a big orchestra,
symphony orchestra.

10:07.140 --> 10:11.178
Yeah, that's... that's my dream.

10:11.211 --> 10:15.983
It's because of the music
Africans survived slavery,

10:16.016 --> 10:18.952
not just physically,
survived psychically.

10:18.986 --> 10:22.756
It's a question of just
improvising instruments.

10:22.790 --> 10:23.290
♪

10:52.753 --> 10:53.253
♪

11:01.261 --> 11:02.696
Thanks so much.

11:02.730 --> 11:04.564
Holy crap, okay.

11:04.597 --> 11:06.033
This is a challenge.

11:06.066 --> 11:07.835
People keep coming up
to me in the street.

11:07.868 --> 11:09.402
The first thing they say is,

11:09.436 --> 11:12.239
"Have you had doubles yet?
Did you get a doubles yet?"

11:12.272 --> 11:15.308
So I'm eating doubles,
all right?

11:15.342 --> 11:18.912
♪

11:18.946 --> 11:21.048
Doubles are a Caribbean take

11:21.081 --> 11:22.750
on the Indian chana bhatura,

11:22.783 --> 11:24.752
two floppy,
tender pieces of soft,

11:24.785 --> 11:26.253
Indian-style bread

11:26.286 --> 11:28.822
loaded with a wet heap
of curried chickpeas,

11:28.856 --> 11:31.191
pepper sauce, and mango.

11:33.093 --> 11:36.396
Structurally,
I have questions here.

11:38.365 --> 11:41.268
Yeah, I don't want seepage.
Seepage is never... never good.

11:41.301 --> 11:43.403
If somebody uses
"seepage" in a sentence,

11:43.436 --> 11:46.974
it... it... nothing good
is gonna happen.

11:48.909 --> 11:50.944
I'm gonna suck the paper.

11:50.978 --> 11:53.613
I don't think
there's meat in here,

11:53.646 --> 11:55.115
but I still like it.

11:55.148 --> 11:57.350
It's really, really good.

11:57.384 --> 12:00.788
♪

12:03.824 --> 12:04.324
♪

12:12.232 --> 12:14.134
A half-century after Trinidad

12:14.167 --> 12:16.403
became independent
of the British Empire,

12:16.436 --> 12:20.207
there are surprisingly
few architectural remnants,

12:20.240 --> 12:21.942
but the face of the country

12:21.975 --> 12:23.777
and its population
were forever changed

12:23.811 --> 12:26.079
when slavery ended in 1834

12:26.113 --> 12:28.548
and Great Britain found itself
in need of cheap,

12:28.581 --> 12:33.120
if not free, labor
to work the plantations.

12:33.153 --> 12:36.323
They found it in East India.

12:36.356 --> 12:39.659
At the abolition of slavery,
the plantation owners

12:39.692 --> 12:41.161
desperately needed to find labor

12:41.194 --> 12:43.230
to fill the void
created by the slaves

12:43.263 --> 12:45.298
who turned their backs
on the plantation

12:45.332 --> 12:48.068
for obvious reasons,
and they looked around.

12:48.101 --> 12:49.837
They tried Portuguese.
They tried Chinese.

12:49.870 --> 12:51.438
They tried many communities

12:51.471 --> 12:53.506
until they found out that
Indians are the best suited

12:53.540 --> 12:55.001
because they were already
planting sugarcane

12:55.008 --> 12:57.644
in India successfully.

12:57.677 --> 13:00.180
♪

13:00.213 --> 13:01.915
Between the end
of outright slavery

13:01.949 --> 13:03.783
and the beginning of
World War I,

13:03.817 --> 13:08.021
150,000 indenturedservants
were brought here from India.

13:08.055 --> 13:12.192
Indentured servitude
is slavery by another name.

13:12.225 --> 13:14.995
The people brought here
from India were bought, sold,

13:15.028 --> 13:17.530
and treated like property
but were told that

13:17.564 --> 13:20.767
if they completed five years
of often back-breaking labor,

13:20.800 --> 13:23.470
they would be set free.

13:26.506 --> 13:27.006
♪

13:31.144 --> 13:33.646
Noon on a Monday,
ordinarily a workday,

13:33.680 --> 13:36.616
but today the Singh family
is having a boys' river wine.

13:40.587 --> 13:43.556
Chan, the patriarch,
is a retired diplomat.

13:43.590 --> 13:46.559
His son, Keshav,
is a music producer.

13:46.593 --> 13:49.796
Uncle Charlie is
in charge of the cooking.

13:49.829 --> 13:52.065
♪

13:52.099 --> 13:54.667
How far back does the family go?

13:54.701 --> 13:57.404
This family goes back to 1845.

13:57.437 --> 13:59.506
1845?
Those were hard times.

13:59.539 --> 14:02.409
Life was not good for y...
For the family in India.

14:02.442 --> 14:03.750
There was poverty,
there was wars

14:03.776 --> 14:05.005
and all sorts of things,
and yes.

14:05.012 --> 14:06.313
- Famine.
- They came into real

14:06.346 --> 14:08.015
hard times here
because the Indian

14:08.048 --> 14:11.018
immigrants from India
replaced the liberated slaves,

14:11.051 --> 14:12.819
and the conditions
were not very different.

14:12.852 --> 14:15.555
Difficult times, but it was
a means to social mobility

14:15.588 --> 14:19.092
and away from
the situation in India.

14:19.126 --> 14:22.029
We part of the descendents
of that generation.

14:22.062 --> 14:22.562
♪

14:29.802 --> 14:30.938
Hey!

14:33.740 --> 14:37.244
Start with one whole duck,
hack into pieces,

14:37.277 --> 14:41.114
rub with lime juice, season
with hot peppers, garlic,

14:41.148 --> 14:43.951
and the tropical herb
shado beni.

14:43.984 --> 14:47.354
Add generous helpings
of masala and curry powder.

14:47.387 --> 14:50.357
Marinate for a bit,
then sear in oil,

14:50.390 --> 14:53.626
then simmer in coconut milk
until tender.

14:53.660 --> 14:55.462
Mmm, man, that's good.

14:55.495 --> 14:57.464
The pepper's soft.
Really hot peppers.

14:57.497 --> 14:59.466
- Yeah.
- That's really good.

14:59.499 --> 15:01.401
We got to kill some more ducks
'cause that is...

15:01.434 --> 15:03.603
When we have it like this,

15:03.636 --> 15:05.805
when we're drinking
before the actual meal,

15:05.838 --> 15:08.141
it's like an appetizer,
but we call it cutters

15:08.175 --> 15:09.977
because it cuts the alcohol.

15:10.010 --> 15:11.611
Yeah.

15:11.644 --> 15:15.282
Right, I'm sobering up
as we speak.

15:15.315 --> 15:16.984
So, look,
you're all Trinidadian?

15:17.017 --> 15:18.418
- Mm-hmm.
- Yes.

15:18.451 --> 15:19.953
It's Trinidad first,
Indian second.

15:19.987 --> 15:20.988
- Yeah.
- 'Cause, I mean,

15:21.021 --> 15:22.222
when the Indians came,

15:22.255 --> 15:23.623
you know,
160-something years ago,

15:23.656 --> 15:26.059
there was a disconnect
with the motherland.

15:26.093 --> 15:27.560
Most of these Indian
were promised

15:27.594 --> 15:29.496
that they were going
for a short tenure

15:29.529 --> 15:33.433
to make a lot of money
and then return home.

15:33.466 --> 15:36.269
They gave return passage
or land... or land.

15:36.303 --> 15:39.172
So when the first Indians
took the option to go back,

15:39.206 --> 15:41.241
couldn't find their families.
Right.

15:41.274 --> 15:43.310
And those who found
their family were rejected

15:43.343 --> 15:45.105
because they said, "You guys
abandoned us for five years."

15:45.112 --> 15:46.413
- Wow.
- "You may as well take

15:46.446 --> 15:48.148
that five acres of land
and stay there."

15:48.181 --> 15:51.351
So there's no closure
to descendants like us

15:51.384 --> 15:53.653
who have not found
any connection

15:53.686 --> 15:56.223
between our families in India.

15:58.858 --> 16:02.295
Soft paratha dough
is cooked on a massive tawa

16:02.329 --> 16:06.833
and slathered with ghee.

16:06.866 --> 16:10.137
But here, just as
it's reaching peak flakiness,

16:10.170 --> 16:13.373
it gets a beating.

16:13.406 --> 16:14.774
Here they call it buss-up-shut,

16:14.807 --> 16:15.942
which means "burst up shirt."

16:15.975 --> 16:17.377
- Burst up shirt?
- Yeah.

16:17.410 --> 16:18.638
Because they'd make
a huge paratha,

16:18.645 --> 16:20.213
and then they whack it
with two sticks.

16:20.247 --> 16:21.841
Oh, okay, I thought
they were talking about

16:21.848 --> 16:24.317
what's gonna happen
to my shirt after I eat it.

16:27.087 --> 16:28.388
What about skin color?

16:28.421 --> 16:29.722
Look, you look at Jamaica,

16:29.756 --> 16:30.823
you look at Haiti.

16:30.857 --> 16:32.459
I don't care what they say,

16:32.492 --> 16:37.230
but what they do is it's still
a powerful determinant

16:37.264 --> 16:40.533
of where your status is in the...
In a power structure.

16:40.567 --> 16:42.369
- Yeah.
- Does that exist here?

16:42.402 --> 16:44.904
It's not something that
has consumed our imagination.

16:44.937 --> 16:49.409
Being Trinidadian is not
necessarily color-tone oriented,

16:49.442 --> 16:52.011
but it's more... and I think
what people really revel in

16:52.045 --> 16:54.247
and enjoy
is the common experiences.

16:54.281 --> 16:57.650
The food is the glue
that binds the society together.

16:57.684 --> 17:00.220
In spite of the problem
that we have here,

17:00.253 --> 17:02.021
we are still one
of the most harmonious,

17:02.055 --> 17:03.656
multiethnic society
in the world,

17:03.690 --> 17:06.393
and the multi-ethnicity
of Trinidad,

17:06.425 --> 17:08.528
the bigger multi-religious
tolerance

17:08.560 --> 17:10.696
are examples
for the world to follow.

17:10.730 --> 17:12.598
We are a small island,
and if you don't learn

17:12.632 --> 17:14.434
to live together,
you have to live in the sea.

17:14.467 --> 17:17.704
We have to.
Right?

