18:24.137 --> 18:27.507
It started in 1898,
more than 100 years ago.

18:27.540 --> 18:31.344
Most of the Christians were
being persecuted by the Turks,

18:31.378 --> 18:36.449
so there was an exodus
of Christians leaving Syria.

18:36.483 --> 18:38.951
They boarded
the ships from Beirut,

18:38.985 --> 18:42.355
and as long as it
was heading west,

18:42.389 --> 18:46.293
they thought they were
going to America.

18:46.326 --> 18:48.528
Many of our parents
landed in Trinidad,

18:48.561 --> 18:50.497
and that's when we started.

18:50.530 --> 18:53.633
That's the first generation.

18:53.666 --> 18:55.702
Just outside of Port of Spain,

18:55.735 --> 18:59.439
Bayshore is one of the priciest
neighborhoods in the country.

18:59.472 --> 19:01.374
I'm here as a guest
of the Sabgavuds,

19:01.408 --> 19:04.877
a successful family
of Lebanese Syrians.

19:04.911 --> 19:07.714
- Look at... isn't this amazing?
- Beirut.

19:07.747 --> 19:10.717
Oh, yes, like Beirut.
You know arak?

19:10.750 --> 19:12.352
- I do indeed.
- Would you like arak?

19:12.385 --> 19:13.686
A little ice and some water

19:13.720 --> 19:15.322
would be perfect.
It would be perfect.

19:15.355 --> 19:17.890
My drink of choice is
Grey Goose and coconut water.

19:17.924 --> 19:21.060
The family's story
is not an uncommon one.

19:21.093 --> 19:22.562
The first members came here

19:22.595 --> 19:24.964
during the collapse
of the Ottoman Empire,

19:24.997 --> 19:26.699
arriving penniless.

19:26.733 --> 19:29.402
They worked their way up
as textile merchants

19:29.436 --> 19:31.571
and branched out
to run businesses that sell

19:31.604 --> 19:34.474
everything from medical
equipment to real estate.

19:34.507 --> 19:38.245
And how large is
the community now in Trinidad?

19:38.278 --> 19:39.812
A little under 5,000.

19:39.846 --> 19:42.815
That's still a fairly
small percentage of the...

19:42.849 --> 19:44.251
Extremely small.

19:44.284 --> 19:47.554
Actually, we are the smallest
ethnic group in Trinidad.

19:47.587 --> 19:50.089
But the most powerful,
almost the most powerful.

19:50.122 --> 19:51.691
Small but the
most powerful, huh?

19:51.724 --> 19:53.326
That's not bragging.

19:53.360 --> 19:58.598
Syrian-Lebanese merchant class
are generally seen as the elite.

19:58.631 --> 20:00.433
Actually, I'm very big
in the food business.

20:00.467 --> 20:02.369
I have a 120 restaurants.

20:02.402 --> 20:04.404
Call me the Starbucks
of the Caribbean.

20:06.539 --> 20:09.276
I can't tell you how happy
I am about this meal.

20:09.309 --> 20:11.411
I love, love the food.

20:13.880 --> 20:15.615
This is raw kibbeh,

20:15.648 --> 20:17.717
the best raw kibbeh
you'll ever eat in your life.

20:17.750 --> 20:19.719
- Yeah.
- This is the fried version,

20:19.752 --> 20:21.621
which is stuffed
with the nice stuffing,

20:21.654 --> 20:24.424
and then we have
the typical hummus.

20:24.457 --> 20:26.926
This is muhammara,
which is made from chili paste

20:26.959 --> 20:30.530
and ground nuts,
the best muhammara in Trinidad.

20:30.563 --> 20:32.432
Then we have falafel patties.

20:32.465 --> 20:34.126
We have grilled wings
with garlic, which is...

20:34.133 --> 20:35.468
Every Arab loves,

20:35.502 --> 20:37.470
Fish in tahini sauce.
You ever had that?

20:37.504 --> 20:39.306
- Yeah, beautiful.
- See, I'm gonna pour

20:39.339 --> 20:42.642
some olive oil over
our lovely things

20:42.675 --> 20:44.143
'cause olive oil is a must.

20:44.176 --> 20:46.879
I mean, and how closely
do people stay in contact

20:46.913 --> 20:47.837
with family or relatives

20:47.847 --> 20:50.817
back in Lebanon or Syria
if at all?

20:50.850 --> 20:53.085
- Not very much.
- We are Trinidadians too.

20:53.119 --> 20:56.423
As much as we are Lebanese
and Syrian, we are Trinidadians.

20:56.456 --> 20:59.626
Trinidad has been good to us,
and we know it.

20:59.659 --> 21:01.428
But life is good here
in Trinidad.

21:01.461 --> 21:02.829
Life is very good,

21:02.862 --> 21:04.964
but there is a measure
of concern in the fact

21:04.997 --> 21:08.635
that at one time we used
to have a huge middle class

21:08.668 --> 21:10.770
which was a sort of a security

21:10.803 --> 21:13.005
in terms
of any possible conflict

21:13.039 --> 21:15.174
between the haves
and the have-not.

21:15.207 --> 21:18.411
But now that's eroding,
and they're getting poorer,

21:18.445 --> 21:20.780
so they're starting
to get angry.

21:20.813 --> 21:23.850
What do you think
the biggest danger is right now?

21:23.883 --> 21:25.518
Civil commotion.

21:25.552 --> 21:27.186
- Yes.
- Civil commotion?

21:27.219 --> 21:30.657
Yeah. We have a crime problem
related to gangs.

21:30.690 --> 21:32.992
Gang warfare.
Related to gang warfare.

21:33.025 --> 21:36.896
It ain't all good for
everybody here by a long shot.

21:42.402 --> 21:45.872
Trinidad, with a population
of only 1.3 million people,

21:45.905 --> 21:49.842
had 460 murders last year,
giving Port of Spain

21:49.876 --> 21:52.545
a per capita murder rate
higher than Detroit,

21:52.579 --> 21:55.014
Oakland, or Chicago.

21:55.047 --> 21:57.450
Mark Bassant covers
the subjects of drug

21:57.484 --> 22:01.220
and gang-related violence
as an investigative journalist.

22:01.253 --> 22:03.890
People want you dead?

22:03.923 --> 22:05.392
You could say that.

22:05.425 --> 22:07.394
Who wants you dead,
do you think?

22:07.427 --> 22:08.895
Well, two years ago I did

22:08.928 --> 22:10.863
a piece about
the state prosecutor,

22:10.897 --> 22:12.799
Dana Seetahal,
who was shot dead.

22:12.832 --> 22:15.234
When state prosecutor
Dana Seetahal left

22:15.267 --> 22:18.738
the Ma Pau car park just
before midnight on May 3rd,

22:18.771 --> 22:22.008
she had no inclination it
would be her last moments alive.

22:22.041 --> 22:25.211
When Mark began to look into
the murder of the prosecutor,

22:25.244 --> 22:26.679
an informant told him

22:26.713 --> 22:29.582
there was a $20,000 contract
on his life.

22:29.616 --> 22:32.485
They had people following me
over a period of time,

22:32.519 --> 22:34.721
some law enforcement officers
and so on,

22:34.754 --> 22:38.425
so my company put me on a plane.

22:38.458 --> 22:40.359
I went... I stayed
under an assumed name

22:40.393 --> 22:44.363
for about three months in
a location outside of Trinidad.

22:44.397 --> 22:48.935
Generally speaking, when
people like that want you dead,

22:48.968 --> 22:50.937
they get you.

22:50.970 --> 22:52.605
Why are you back?

22:52.639 --> 22:55.341
I guess, to quote from a great

22:55.374 --> 22:56.843
U.S. journalist,
Walter Cronkite,

22:56.876 --> 22:58.578
"It's not what you
want people to know.

22:58.611 --> 23:00.246
It's what they need to know."

23:00.279 --> 23:02.949
We need to have people held
accountable for certain things.

23:02.982 --> 23:08.020
With drug trafficking being one
of the biggest businesses

23:08.054 --> 23:09.288
in the world,

23:09.321 --> 23:12.525
Trinidad continues to be
a major transshipment point

23:12.559 --> 23:14.060
for drug dealers

23:14.093 --> 23:17.296
to get that product out
to North America

23:17.329 --> 23:18.931
and to Europe,

23:18.965 --> 23:22.134
so you find now
the explosion of violence

23:22.168 --> 23:24.136
that we have is for those

23:24.170 --> 23:27.774
that are involved locally
with the drug trafficking,

23:27.807 --> 23:29.642
this fight for territory.

23:29.676 --> 23:33.546
An estimated $3.5 billion
worth of narcotics

23:33.580 --> 23:35.882
moves through
the Caribbean each year.

23:35.915 --> 23:37.817
Trinidad's porous borders,

23:37.850 --> 23:40.419
busy port,
proximity to Venezuela,

23:40.453 --> 23:43.155
and the inevitable corruption
that comes with numbers

23:43.189 --> 23:45.124
and threats like that make it,

23:45.157 --> 23:48.628
unfortunately,
an ideal transshipment point.

23:50.497 --> 23:54.501
How bad is high-level
corruption alleged to be?

23:54.534 --> 23:57.136
Fairly deep.
I think that the complicity

23:57.169 --> 24:00.607
comes across the law
enforcement agencies,

24:00.640 --> 24:05.578
customs, police officers,
even at higher levels.

24:05.612 --> 24:08.848
And with corruption,
poverty, hopelessness,

24:08.881 --> 24:10.917
add some radical ideology
to that,

24:10.950 --> 24:13.853
and Trinidad has proved
relatively fertile ground

24:13.886 --> 24:17.189
for the recruitment
of ISIS fighters...

24:17.223 --> 24:18.791
and terrorists.

24:18.825 --> 24:21.761
It's quite alarming,
Trinidadian nationals

24:21.794 --> 24:25.131
being one of the highest
in the region going to Syria,

24:25.164 --> 24:28.034
and it's over a hundred
on a list, FBI list.

24:28.067 --> 24:31.203
They feel that it's their
calling from ISIS

24:31.237 --> 24:32.505
that they need to go.

24:32.539 --> 24:34.040
So what's the future look like?

24:34.073 --> 24:35.942
What do you think?
How's it gonna go?

24:35.975 --> 24:38.645
Wow, that's a loaded question.

24:38.678 --> 24:40.880
There are really good people
here in Trinidad.

24:40.913 --> 24:42.381
They're really,
really good people

24:42.414 --> 24:44.483
that can make a difference
on all fronts.

24:44.517 --> 24:46.819
If we go down the path
that we go now,

24:46.853 --> 24:49.989
there will be all bad.

25:03.202 --> 25:03.702
♪

25:13.780 --> 25:16.215
In 1990 the radical
Islamic group

25:16.248 --> 25:20.419
Jamaat al Muslimeen laid siege
to Trinidad's parliament,

25:20.452 --> 25:23.690
claiming they were responding
to rising inequality, poverty,

25:23.723 --> 25:26.826
and religious discrimination.

25:26.859 --> 25:30.597
What ensued was a violent
and terrifying disaster.

25:30.630 --> 25:33.265
26 people were killed
in skirmishes,

25:33.299 --> 25:36.002
and the hostage-takers,
would-be revolutionaries,

25:36.035 --> 25:40.272
gave up in exchange
for clemency after six days.

25:40.306 --> 25:43.075
Little changed.

25:46.112 --> 25:49.616
♪

25:49.649 --> 25:53.252
Muhammad Muwakil's father took
part in the attempted coup.

25:53.285 --> 25:54.721
He grew up, in fact,

25:54.754 --> 25:57.056
in the Jamaat al Muslimeen
compound,

25:57.089 --> 26:00.627
but he's chosen to take
a different path, music.

26:04.496 --> 26:07.266
He's the lead singer
of Freetown Collective,

26:07.299 --> 26:09.802
a band named after
a Port of Spain neighborhood

26:09.836 --> 26:12.238
that was once a settlement
for freed slaves.

26:12.271 --> 26:15.742
♪ They say we can't
write no love songs ♪

26:15.775 --> 26:18.878
♪ Live fast and we die young ♪

26:18.911 --> 26:21.981
♪ They say we doomed
to fail, yeah ♪

26:22.014 --> 26:24.150
♪ They say we doomed to fail

26:24.183 --> 26:26.318
♪ They say we prone to
violence ♪

26:26.352 --> 26:30.389
- ♪ Violence
- ♪ And a sinking silence

26:30.422 --> 26:34.260
♪ They don't know what they say,
no, no, no, no, no ♪

26:34.293 --> 26:36.095
♪ No, no, no, no

26:36.128 --> 26:37.830
Much like a lot of reggae,

26:37.864 --> 26:40.066
his music calls
out the social ills

26:40.099 --> 26:41.901
that have been
disproportionately visited

26:41.934 --> 26:45.337
on the Afro-Caribbean
population.

26:45.371 --> 26:48.474
♪ I see bodies lying
in the streets ♪

26:48.507 --> 26:52.679
♪ Nations collapse
in the midday heat ♪

26:52.712 --> 26:55.848
♪ Lord, I need to cool my head ♪

26:55.882 --> 26:57.750
♪ My head

26:57.784 --> 27:00.352
♪ They calling it
a brave new world ♪

27:00.386 --> 27:03.322
♪ Freedom for brave
new boys and girls ♪

27:03.355 --> 27:07.860
♪ What good is freedom
if you're dead? ♪

27:07.894 --> 27:09.528
You look around
my city right now,

27:09.561 --> 27:11.356
and a lot of young people
are choosing death over life

27:11.363 --> 27:13.058
because the life that they look
at doesn't feel like

27:13.065 --> 27:14.633
it's substantiated by anything.

27:14.667 --> 27:17.036
In the Freetown neighborhood
now called Belmont,

27:17.069 --> 27:20.539
he lives with his
81-year-old granny, Neela Natu.

27:20.572 --> 27:23.509
The thing is that recently
we've had a lot of people,

27:23.542 --> 27:25.377
people who I've known,
who I grew up with

27:25.411 --> 27:28.114
who've gone to fight in Syria,
who've left here.

27:28.147 --> 27:31.517
I mean, they will tell you
that the official count is 140.

27:31.550 --> 27:33.219
I would say it's more.

27:33.252 --> 27:35.021
- You'd say it's more?
- I'd say it's more.

27:35.054 --> 27:37.556
And why do you think
people would go?

27:37.589 --> 27:38.791
I'd have to go back into

27:38.825 --> 27:40.392
my childhood
to explain that to you.

27:40.426 --> 27:41.728
The coup that happened here

27:41.761 --> 27:43.395
happened when
I was six years old.

27:43.429 --> 27:46.032
They had all these young people
in there who had this idea,

27:46.065 --> 27:47.592
you know, we're going
to build this thing.

27:47.599 --> 27:49.061
There's this community
that's gonna stand up

27:49.068 --> 27:50.502
against what's going on
in Trinidad,

27:50.536 --> 27:52.404
that's going to stand up
against the drugs

27:52.438 --> 27:53.906
and stand up against poverty

27:53.940 --> 27:56.709
and stand up against crime,
and nothing happened.

27:56.743 --> 27:59.011
In none of these causes,

27:59.045 --> 28:03.916
religious fundamentalism
or fervor has not come up.

28:03.950 --> 28:06.218
You... every... every issue
you've mentioned so far

28:06.252 --> 28:08.721
has been perceived
inadequacy of social justice.

28:08.755 --> 28:09.922
Right, yeah.

28:09.956 --> 28:12.759
So these kids
going off to Syria,

28:12.792 --> 28:14.360
do they have any idea
what they're doing?

28:14.393 --> 28:16.188
- No, they do not.
- Or are they just pissed off?

28:16.195 --> 28:18.931
No, they do not. People say
that poverty breeds crime.

28:18.965 --> 28:20.625
I don't think poverty
breeds crime in a sense.

28:20.632 --> 28:24.370
I think exclusion breeds crime
because if I truly care for you,

28:24.403 --> 28:27.539
if I feel like you are a part
of the thing that I exist in,

28:27.573 --> 28:29.341
then I won't... I won't hurt you.

28:29.375 --> 28:31.077
Might come in your house
and steal some food,

28:31.110 --> 28:32.912
but when you see
that kind of violence

28:32.945 --> 28:34.713
being enacted,
you have to ask yourself.

28:34.747 --> 28:36.115
It's not just somebody saying,

28:36.148 --> 28:37.709
"I need this tablecloth.
I'm gonna take this."

28:37.716 --> 28:40.286
No, "I want this tablecloth",

28:40.319 --> 28:42.621
"and you, you had this
tablecloth for too long,

28:42.654 --> 28:44.483
"so you know what,
I'm gonna take this out on you.

28:44.490 --> 28:46.558
This is gonna happen.
That's gonna happen."

28:46.592 --> 28:48.360
And that's what
we're seeing now.

28:48.394 --> 28:50.241
I mean, how long can people
put up with something

28:50.262 --> 28:53.399
before they decide this is
enough, you know what I mean?

28:53.432 --> 28:56.435
Would you say that Carnival
and that Carnival attitude,

28:56.468 --> 29:00.206
the liming culture is a...

29:00.239 --> 29:04.410
Might as well be a brilliant
strategy to narcotize

29:04.443 --> 29:07.446
the people into being satisfied
with the status quo?

29:07.479 --> 29:13.219
Everything here is somehow
designed to...

29:13.252 --> 29:16.122
pacify it
without us really realizing,

29:16.155 --> 29:19.758
so our music, which is
supposed to give us adrenaline

29:19.792 --> 29:21.293
as well as sleeping pills
sometimes,

29:21.327 --> 29:22.995
it's just doling
out sleeping pills.

29:23.029 --> 29:25.097
Like, go ahead, enjoy yourself.
Enjoy yourself.

29:25.131 --> 29:26.432
Enjoy yourself.
You are Trini.

29:26.465 --> 29:28.901
Trini means fun-loving and happy

29:28.935 --> 29:31.070
and whatever
despite whatever it is.

29:31.103 --> 29:31.938
Ah.

29:34.807 --> 29:39.478
It's a big and delicious
home-cooked meal.

29:39.511 --> 29:40.339
I caught this myself.

29:40.346 --> 29:42.081
- Really?
- Yes, sir.

29:42.114 --> 29:44.283
- Red snapper?
- Yeah, yeah.

29:44.316 --> 29:46.185
The snapper is seasoned
with lime juice,

29:46.218 --> 29:49.121
shado beni and onion.

29:49.155 --> 29:51.290
What's this dish called?
Is there a name for it?

29:51.323 --> 29:53.192
- This is called oil down.
- Oil down?

29:53.225 --> 29:54.526
- Yeah.
- For oil down

29:54.560 --> 29:55.962
they season breadfruit

29:55.995 --> 29:58.030
and meat with dasheen
and green figs,

29:58.064 --> 30:00.366
then simmer in coconut milk.

30:00.399 --> 30:02.501
And, well, she uses pork,
as you can see,

30:02.534 --> 30:05.204
which I... now I can't have any,
so that's okay.

30:05.237 --> 30:07.139
Now your grandma, not a Muslim?

30:07.173 --> 30:11.377
No, the Roman Catholic-est
of all Roman Catholics.

30:11.410 --> 30:14.146
- Old-school?
- Sacred heart up on the wall.

30:14.180 --> 30:17.116
I got a kind of a perfect one
for you, so you have this.

30:17.149 --> 30:19.118
- Oh, beautiful, thank you.
- Pastel.

30:19.151 --> 30:22.488
This is mostly when
the Spaniards where here,

30:22.521 --> 30:24.556
introduced this.
This is a Spanish one.

30:24.590 --> 30:28.227
Pastels are the Caribbean
cousin to the tamale.

30:28.260 --> 30:30.329
Minced beef is wrapped
in cornmeal dough,

30:30.362 --> 30:33.799
then in banana leaf,
then steamed.

30:33.832 --> 30:35.401
Table for sure.

30:35.434 --> 30:37.904
She will feed you till
you burst like any grandmother.

30:37.937 --> 30:39.671
You know, right?
Yeah.

30:39.705 --> 30:42.208
- I'll be well looked after.
- And that is once a year.

30:42.241 --> 30:44.210
- So when do these ordinarily...
- Christmastime.

30:44.243 --> 30:46.578
Christmas, oh.
This is very, very delicious.

30:46.612 --> 30:48.714
Thank you very much,
and one thing I've asked about.

30:48.747 --> 30:50.349
Why you didn't put ice
in his glass?

30:50.382 --> 30:52.051
It's good.
It's fine.

30:52.084 --> 30:54.053
So he must say thanks
to whatever you made.

30:54.086 --> 30:55.754
Tell Muhammad it's not good.

30:55.787 --> 30:59.725
See how... see how
that generation, very proper,

30:59.758 --> 31:01.427
like, very, very proper,

31:01.460 --> 31:03.896
and one of the things
about Trinidad is that...

31:03.930 --> 31:05.497
Muhammad, don't bad-talk me.

31:05.531 --> 31:08.567
I'm not bad-talking you.
I only speak the truth.

31:08.600 --> 31:12.905
That generation very much
believed in independence

31:12.939 --> 31:14.606
and that this nation
would be something,

31:14.640 --> 31:16.108
and then they told
their children,

31:16.142 --> 31:18.244
"Study and come
and help this nation.

31:18.277 --> 31:20.279
Build this nation,
and it's gonna be something."

31:20.312 --> 31:22.781
And that generation, which was
my parents, they did that.

31:22.814 --> 31:24.116
Right.

31:24.150 --> 31:27.286
And then they had kids,
you know?

31:27.319 --> 31:29.755
And all of a sudden it was like,
okay, all these things

31:29.788 --> 31:32.058
you have been saying about
building a nation and whatever,

31:32.091 --> 31:34.153
how come I'm seeing these people
benefitting, and I'm not?

31:34.160 --> 31:36.155
How come I'm seeing this, I'm
seeing that, I'm seeing that?

31:36.162 --> 31:37.990
And there were very few answers,
you know what I mean?

31:37.997 --> 31:39.465
So who runs this country?

31:39.498 --> 31:42.101
Like everywhere else, that 1%.
Like everywhere else.

31:42.134 --> 31:44.971
Everybody here
is very eager to tell you

31:45.004 --> 31:47.139
what a wonderful mix it is,

31:47.173 --> 31:49.241
and the food, if you look at it,

31:49.275 --> 31:52.778
it does... is this incredibly
harmonious stew pot.

31:52.811 --> 31:54.246
Right.

31:54.280 --> 31:56.248
But I guess life
doesn't work as well as food.

31:56.282 --> 31:58.250
No. The only thing
we've agreed on in this place

31:58.284 --> 31:59.718
is how much salt
to put in anything.

31:59.751 --> 32:02.321
So that's the only thing
we've agreed on.

32:02.354 --> 32:04.090
♪

32:04.123 --> 32:07.259
♪ Man we on a mission

32:07.293 --> 32:09.328
♪ A whole world to change

32:09.361 --> 32:12.831
♪ Yeah a whole world
to change ♪

32:12.864 --> 32:13.364
♪

32:29.115 --> 32:30.849
♪

32:30.882 --> 32:33.752
Trinidad, it should be
pointed out right now,

32:33.785 --> 32:35.521
before you start packing
your Speedo

32:35.554 --> 32:38.657
and your cocoa butter,
is an industrial island.

32:42.461 --> 32:44.330
And like so many places,

32:44.363 --> 32:47.933
industrialization
is changing the landscape here,

32:47.966 --> 32:50.202
but some things persist,

32:50.236 --> 32:53.539
remain, echo from
all the way back then...

32:58.910 --> 33:03.549
When West African slaves
would covertly do this,

33:03.582 --> 33:05.351
Calinda.

33:05.384 --> 33:08.020
This martial art,
based on our research,

33:08.054 --> 33:10.989
is maybe 500, 600 years old.

33:11.023 --> 33:12.558
Stick fighting variations

33:12.591 --> 33:14.393
occur throughout the Caribbean,

33:14.426 --> 33:17.329
but in Trinidad and Tobago it's,
like, deep in their blood.

33:22.201 --> 33:24.803
This martial art was illegal
for many, many years.

33:24.836 --> 33:26.338
Yes?
Yeah.

33:26.372 --> 33:28.433
I mean, certainly during
slavery times it was illegal.

33:28.440 --> 33:30.376
To this day,
I believe there's still laws

33:30.409 --> 33:33.011
on our books
that ban this stick,

33:33.045 --> 33:34.980
and if you're caught with it,
you could go to jail.

33:35.013 --> 33:38.084
The laws of slavery times
forced this sport underground.

33:38.117 --> 33:42.854
Like Capoeira, it often had
to be disguised as a dance,

33:42.888 --> 33:44.590
but this ain't no dance.

33:44.623 --> 33:46.518
The guys with the whip
and the guys with the stick

33:46.525 --> 33:49.495
were all the guys saying,
"You have not broken us.

33:49.528 --> 33:54.100
We will continue to resist
to the ends of time."

33:54.133 --> 33:54.633
♪

34:06.945 --> 34:10.581
Rondel Benjamin and Keegan
Taylor studied fighting styles

34:10.616 --> 34:12.451
from around the world
before coming around

34:12.484 --> 34:14.953
to their own
homegrown martial art.

34:14.985 --> 34:16.688
Now, what's legal?

34:16.722 --> 34:19.625
- What's not legal is...
- Oh, they say what's not legal?

34:19.658 --> 34:22.860
♪

34:22.893 --> 34:25.197
I can't hit to the legs, knees.

34:25.231 --> 34:26.965
- You can't?
- Can't.

34:26.998 --> 34:28.927
Oh, damn, 'cause that would
be the first thing I'd think of.

34:28.934 --> 34:31.263
I'm thinking, "I got to get that
knee... that knee in particular."

34:31.270 --> 34:33.371
Now, to be honest,
in stick fighting,

34:33.405 --> 34:36.542
legal and illegal is a concept,

34:36.574 --> 34:41.380
but it doesn't stop that kind
of stuff from happening.

34:41.413 --> 34:43.449
Right, but I mean,
let's face it.

34:43.482 --> 34:45.384
This is a pretty heavy object.
Yeah.

34:45.417 --> 34:47.286
I get a good swing, a tee off,

34:47.319 --> 34:51.790
and I get a clean shot
on the head...

34:51.822 --> 34:53.458
This is what the
New York Police Department

34:53.492 --> 34:54.826
would call a deadly weapon.

34:54.860 --> 34:56.661
- Yes, sir.
- If I'm fighting,

34:56.695 --> 35:00.166
if I'm really fighting,
I'm a monster.

35:00.199 --> 35:01.633
I got to look you down.

35:01.667 --> 35:03.302
I got to kill you.
I got to dig you up.

35:03.335 --> 35:05.171
I got to bury you.
I got to murder you.

35:05.204 --> 35:06.772
I got to take you out.

35:06.805 --> 35:10.342
♪

35:10.376 --> 35:12.144
The demon in me
is gonna come out,

35:12.178 --> 35:13.912
but I call that demon
to work with me.

35:13.945 --> 35:16.014
King David is one of
the old-school street fighters

35:16.047 --> 35:19.851
who has kept this form
from fading over the years.

35:19.885 --> 35:20.385
♪

35:24.523 --> 35:26.024
As in Brazil and the Deep South,

35:26.057 --> 35:28.860
African slaves were
given little to work with

35:28.894 --> 35:30.529
when it came time for the meal.

35:30.562 --> 35:32.698
More often than not,
if they wanted meat,

35:32.731 --> 35:36.635
they had to make do with what
the slave masters did not want,

35:36.668 --> 35:39.705
a tongue here, cow foot there.

35:39.738 --> 35:41.707
Here, as elsewhere,
they figured out

35:41.740 --> 35:44.343
how to make something
delicious and tender

35:44.376 --> 35:47.045
from whatever there was,
like souse.

35:47.078 --> 35:49.815
Pig foot is pickled
in shado beni, onions

35:49.848 --> 35:51.217
and hot peppers,

35:51.250 --> 35:53.719
and then topped off
with cucumbers.

35:58.757 --> 36:01.627
This is a martial art.
You either win or you lose.

36:01.660 --> 36:03.229
- Correct.
- How do you win?

36:03.262 --> 36:04.530
What decides winner?

36:04.563 --> 36:06.798
Who draws blood first win.

36:06.832 --> 36:09.235
All it requires
is the end result.

36:11.403 --> 36:13.305
All you have to do
is cut the guy.

36:15.173 --> 36:18.210
Blood is blood.

36:18.244 --> 36:21.747
What's the worst injury
you've ever had in a fight?

36:21.780 --> 36:24.850
This finger.

36:24.883 --> 36:28.254
What's the worst injury
you've seen in a fight?

36:28.287 --> 36:32.491
I lost... I see
a man lost the eye.

36:32.524 --> 36:35.093
And also I saw a man die.

36:35.126 --> 36:36.895
You have to be a real warrior,

36:36.928 --> 36:38.397
a born, born, born fighter

36:38.430 --> 36:39.931
to stand up there and face

36:39.965 --> 36:43.302
that demon
which walk in like a man.

37:02.788 --> 37:05.123
30 miles east of Trinidad,

37:05.156 --> 37:08.627
its sister island, Tobago.

37:08.660 --> 37:10.729
A whole different vibe
around here,

37:10.762 --> 37:12.398
more like what you'd hope for

37:12.431 --> 37:13.792
when you'd waddle away
from the buffet

37:13.799 --> 37:17.703
on the S.S. Norwalk
cruise ship.

37:17.736 --> 37:21.373
Lazy beach days,
boat drinks, villas,

37:21.407 --> 37:23.309
all set to a calypso beat.

37:26.345 --> 37:29.214
♪

37:32.351 --> 37:34.986
♪

37:35.020 --> 37:36.822
Oh, solo.

37:36.855 --> 37:39.090
In the 1800s slaves
would sing the news

37:39.124 --> 37:41.460
and gossip of the day
in a Creole patois

37:41.493 --> 37:42.961
to an African beat.

37:42.994 --> 37:46.064
Later musicians
added European-style melodies,

37:46.097 --> 37:49.100
and calypso was born.

37:49.134 --> 37:51.770
The longtime reigning queen
of this music

37:51.803 --> 37:56.141
and absolute pioneer
of the form is Calypso Rose.

37:58.777 --> 38:00.679
♪ They say that
I reign too long ♪

38:00.712 --> 38:03.515
♪ Forgetting that
my constitution is strong ♪

38:03.549 --> 38:06.585
♪ Instead of respecting
my long, long reign ♪

38:06.618 --> 38:09.855
♪ They making threat
to take down my name ♪

38:09.888 --> 38:15.461
♪ I've been breaking down walls
ever since I was tall ♪

38:15.494 --> 38:17.829
♪ They would stand up
tall and strong ♪

38:17.863 --> 38:21.533
♪ Like a wrecking ball,
I go knock them down ♪

38:21.567 --> 38:23.869
♪ They say that
I reign too long ♪

38:23.902 --> 38:25.371
Come on, baby!

38:25.404 --> 38:27.873
She was the first woman
to win the Calypso King title,

38:27.906 --> 38:29.941
which tells you what
the environment was like

38:29.975 --> 38:33.211
at the time for a female artist.

38:33.244 --> 38:35.814
♪ Everywhere I reign supreme

38:35.847 --> 38:38.684
♪ The one and only
calypso queen ♪

38:38.717 --> 38:41.019
♪ No man alive or dead

38:41.052 --> 38:45.190
♪ Could come and take
the crown off me head ♪

38:45.223 --> 38:47.559
♪

38:47.593 --> 38:49.127
Rose grew up in a large

38:49.160 --> 38:51.530
and strict
Baptist family in Tobago

38:51.563 --> 38:53.064
until she was nine years old

38:53.098 --> 38:55.901
and was sent to live
with her aunt in Trinidad,

38:55.934 --> 38:58.904
so she grew up
with a foot in each island.

38:58.937 --> 39:01.673
What's the difference between
growing up in Trinidad

39:01.707 --> 39:03.842
and growing up in Tobago?
It's much different.

39:03.875 --> 39:07.379
Tobagonians are 99 1/2% African.

39:07.413 --> 39:11.016
They're African
slave descendants.

39:11.049 --> 39:13.419
The culture is more African,

39:13.452 --> 39:18.256
and this, this here
is the cornmeal cou co...

39:18.289 --> 39:20.526
They call it fufu in Africa,

39:20.559 --> 39:22.694
but in Tobago they say cou co...

39:22.728 --> 39:24.062
And this is callaloo?

39:24.095 --> 39:26.031
And this is the callaloo
made from the leaves-

39:26.064 --> 39:28.667
- Dasheens.
- Of dasheen, you know?

39:28.700 --> 39:30.936
But the great thing is the crab.

39:33.972 --> 39:35.941
♪

39:35.974 --> 39:40.011
Everybody come to Tobago
must eat crab and dumpling.

39:40.045 --> 39:42.280
They dry coconut.

39:42.313 --> 39:46.518
They grated the coconut,
and the juice of that coconut,

39:46.552 --> 39:47.953
they put it in the pot

39:47.986 --> 39:50.422
with your little ingredients
like tomato, onion,

39:50.456 --> 39:54.192
thyme and your curry.

39:54.225 --> 39:55.794
Crunch it up.

39:55.827 --> 39:58.296
Good teeth.

39:58.329 --> 40:00.466
If you have false teeth,
be careful.

40:00.499 --> 40:03.134
All right.
Yeah, so far, so good.

40:03.168 --> 40:05.804
Here's what I...
What really fascinates me,

40:05.837 --> 40:09.541
is you started singing calypso
music and writing songs...

40:09.575 --> 40:10.809
Of course.

40:10.842 --> 40:12.611
At a time when it was only men.

40:12.644 --> 40:13.979
Your father was not...

40:14.012 --> 40:15.881
- My father was against it.
- Against it?

40:15.914 --> 40:18.884
My father was traditional
Baptist minister.

40:18.917 --> 40:22.754
My father say
calypso belong to the devil.

40:22.788 --> 40:26.892
Calypso belongs to the devil,
but it also belonged to men,

40:26.925 --> 40:29.495
and here you are
at age 15 doing...

40:29.528 --> 40:31.329
- Age 13, I start writing.
- 13?

40:31.362 --> 40:36.301
Doing what was considered a
completely revolutionary thing.

40:36.334 --> 40:40.606
What was it about you
that made you strong enough

40:40.639 --> 40:43.509
and different enough
and determined enough

40:43.542 --> 40:46.411
to choose to do such a difficult

40:46.444 --> 40:49.347
and unusual thing
when everybody was against it?

40:49.380 --> 40:52.684
My fans, because some people
at home, they're sad.

40:52.718 --> 40:57.155
They're going through so much
financially, economically,

40:57.188 --> 41:00.025
they're being abused
by their spouse,

41:00.058 --> 41:02.093
and they come out
to have a good time,

41:02.127 --> 41:06.031
and when they come out,
I bring joy to their heart.

41:06.064 --> 41:10.135
So is making
beautiful things enough?

41:10.168 --> 41:12.871
Yes, making
beautiful things enough.

41:12.904 --> 41:16.775
Well, when you start thinking
consciously on beautiful things,

41:16.808 --> 41:19.711
like how the sea is
rolling there...

41:22.881 --> 41:26.384
How the sea is
moving, moving, moving,

41:26.417 --> 41:28.053
making beautiful things
is enough.

41:28.086 --> 41:29.487
It is enough?

41:29.521 --> 41:32.791
♪

41:32.824 --> 41:35.727
No island in the sun
is paradise on Earth,

41:35.761 --> 41:38.296
however it might look
from the concrete blocks,

41:38.329 --> 41:41.366
glass cubicles,
or wood boxes we may live in.

41:41.399 --> 41:43.669
♪

41:43.702 --> 41:45.904
And all the dancing and music

41:45.937 --> 41:47.573
and great food in the world

41:47.606 --> 41:50.408
can never hold together,
by itself,

41:50.441 --> 41:52.644
what would keep us apart.

41:52.678 --> 41:55.013
♪

41:55.046 --> 41:57.248
What might look like
a utopian stew

41:57.282 --> 41:58.750
of ethnicities and cultures

41:58.784 --> 42:01.252
living together
under gently swaying palms

42:01.286 --> 42:05.557
is of course
a far more complicated matter.

42:05.591 --> 42:07.593
♪

42:07.626 --> 42:09.595
But Trinidad
has done better than most

42:09.628 --> 42:12.998
and in proud and unique style.

42:13.031 --> 42:15.533
Solo, solo.

42:15.567 --> 42:16.067
